{{fr-verb}}

# {{lb|fr|uncommon}} to {{l|en|centralize}} {{l|en|community|communities}}, making them (progressively or not) lose their distinct identities to merge into a bigger one
# {{lb|fr|European Union}} to {{l|en|decentralize}} {{l|en|competence|competences}} from the European level to the state level
# {{lb|fr|Belgium}} to transfer {{l|en|competence|competences}} from [[w:Communities, regions, and language areas of Belgium|the linguistic communities]] to the federal state

====Usage notes====
At first glance, one could wonder why in the European context, ''décommunautariser'' means "decentralise", but in Belgium it means "centralise". It is actually very simple.

Before 2009 and the Treaty of Lisbon, the European Union was organised in '''[[w:European Community|communities]]''': the [[w:European Coal and Steel Community|ECSC]], [[w:Euratom|Euratom]], and the [[w:European Economic Community|EEC]] (single market). The prefix {{l|fr|dé-}} being used to make antonyms and generally speaking meaning ''moving away from'', the word evolved into "leaving, moving away from the European communities". And thus, {{l|en|decentralize|decentralizing}} by giving competences to the member states making up the [[w:European Community|European Communities]].

In Belgium, the '''[[w:Communities, regions, and language areas of Belgium|communities]]''' are political areas based on the language spoken here (either French, Flemish, or German). Thus, by "moving away" from those communities, we can only go towards the central government: we {{l|en|centralize}}.

